<bibRefCitation id="B1120BFBFF82FFF5FB20F22AF7A9F9BC" author="Reiskind, J." box="[1273,1426,1594,1618]" pageId="2" pageNumber="581" pagination="163 - 325" refId="ref7181" refString="Reiskind, J. (1969) The spider subfamily Castianeirinae of North and Central America (Araneae, Clubionidae). Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 138, 163 - 325." type="journal article" year="1969">Reiskind 1969</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9D992581FF82FFF5FF4EF290F2EEF8E8" pageId="2" pageNumber="581" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="D53C760AFF82FFF5FF4EF290F2EEF8E8" blockId="2.[151,1436,1664,1978]" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">
<emphasis id="E7F7AA18FF82FFF5FF4EF290F331F974" bold="true" box="[151,266,1664,1690]" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">Diagnosis</emphasis>
(modified from 
<bibRefCitation id="B1120BFBFF82FFF5FE1BF290F04DF975" author="Reiskind, J." box="[450,630,1664,1691]" pageId="2" pageNumber="581" pagination="163 - 325" refId="ref7181" refString="Reiskind, J. (1969) The spider subfamily Castianeirinae of North and Central America (Araneae, Clubionidae). Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 138, 163 - 325." type="journal article" year="1969">Reiskind (1969)</bibRefCitation>
and Rubio &amp; Danişman (2014)). Abdomen with distinct, rugose petiole, second pair of abdominal spines sclerotized to spine-like tubercles and/or spines (except in 
<taxonomicName id="12830D89FF82FFF5FB55F2B5F6DBF950" authorityName="Reiskind" authorityYear="1969" box="[1164,1248,1701,1726]" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Mazax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="581" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ajax">
<emphasis id="E7F7AA18FF82FFF5FB55F2B5F6DBF950" box="[1164,1248,1701,1726]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">M. ajax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), AER recurved, PER slightly recurved to straight, eyes moderately large and approximately equal, with AME slightly smaller than ALE.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9D992581FF82FFF5FF1EF300F6D2F854" pageId="2" pageNumber="581" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="D53C760AFF82FFF5FF1EF300F6D2F854" blockId="2.[151,1436,1664,1978]" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">
<emphasis id="E7F7AA18FF82FFF5FF1EF300F300F8C4" bold="true" box="[199,315,1808,1834]" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">Remarks.</emphasis>
A rugose petiole and abdominal spines can be found in the Asian genus 
<taxonomicName id="12830D89FF82FFF5FB95F300F2E9F8A0" authority="Deeleman-Reinhold, 2001" authorityName="Deeleman-Reinhold" authorityYear="2001" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Serendib" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="581" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E7F7AA18FF82FFF5FB95F300F694F8C4" box="[1100,1199,1808,1834]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">Serendib</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="B1120BFBFF82FFF5FB6DF300F2E9F8A0" author="Deeleman-Reinhold, C. L." pageId="2" pageNumber="581" refId="ref5914" refString="Deeleman-Reinhold, C. L. (2001) Forest spiders of South East Asia: with a revision of the sac and ground spiders (Araneae: Clubionidae, Corinnidae, Liocranidae, Gnaphosidae, Prodidomidae and Trochanterriidae [sic]). Brill, Leiden, 591 pp." type="book" year="2001">Deeleman-Reinhold, 2001</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but 
<taxonomicName id="12830D89FF82FFF5FEDDF324F386F8A0" box="[260,445,1844,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">
<emphasis id="E7F7AA18FF82FFF5FEDDF324F35CF8A0" box="[260,359,1844,1870]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">Serendib</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
have a sub-globose abdomen, a strongly recurved posterior eye row with widely separated eyes, and AME larger than ALE (
<bibRefCitation id="B1120BFBFF82FFF5FDDDF348F112F89C" author="Deeleman-Reinhold, C. L." box="[516,809,1880,1906]" pageId="2" pageNumber="581" refId="ref5914" refString="Deeleman-Reinhold, C. L. (2001) Forest spiders of South East Asia: with a revision of the sac and ground spiders (Araneae: Clubionidae, Corinnidae, Liocranidae, Gnaphosidae, Prodidomidae and Trochanterriidae [sic]). Brill, Leiden, 591 pp." type="book" year="2001">Deeleman-Reinhold 2001</bibRefCitation>
). Species of 
<taxonomicName id="12830D89FF82FFF5FC6AF348F614F89C" authorityName="Pett, Rubio &amp; Perger" authorityYear="2022" box="[947,1071,1880,1906]" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Grismadox" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="581" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E7F7AA18FF82FFF5FC6AF348F614F89C" box="[947,1071,1880,1906]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">Grismadox</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resemble 
<taxonomicName id="12830D89FF82FFF5FB79F349F6D0F89C" authorityName="O. Pickard-Cambridge" authorityYear="1898" box="[1184,1259,1881,1906]" class="Arachnida" family="Corinnidae" genus="Mazax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="581" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="E7F7AA18FF82FFF5FB79F349F6D0F89C" box="[1184,1259,1881,1906]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">Mazax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in their habitus, subequal eyes and the sclerotized second abdominal setae, but can be separated from the latter by a short, smooth petiole, the male palp with both dRTA and vRTA, and females with anterior COs (
<bibRefCitation id="B1120BFBFF82FFF5FBF5F3B0F6E6F854" author="Pett, B. L. &amp; Rubio, G. D. &amp; Perger, R." box="[1068,1245,1952,1978]" pageId="2" pageNumber="581" pagination="1 - 11" refId="ref7076" refString="Pett, B. L., Rubio, G. D. &amp; Perger, R. (2022) Grismadox gen. nov., a new Neotropical genus of ant-resembling spiders (Araneae, Corinnidae, Castianeirinae), including the description of two new species from Bolivia and Paraguay. Zoosystematics &amp; Evolution, 98 (1), 1 - 11. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zse. 98.76677" type="journal article" year="2022">
Pett 
<emphasis id="E7F7AA18FF82FFF5FBB8F3B1F6A2F854" box="[1121,1177,1952,1978]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="581">et al.</emphasis>
2022
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
